    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-12-12T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-12-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="397"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d397">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/14492: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-12-12T12:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 12, 1938—noon.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 12—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>595. Embassy’s 557, November 20, 10 a.m., and previous on Chiang-Clark-Kerr
                    conversations at Changsha. A reliable Chinese official told a member of the
                    Embassy staff on December 11 that the British Government has now replied to the
                    Chinese Government. He stated that the British note is couched in non-committal
                    terms and cannot for this reason be considered as satisfactory. He added however
                    that the tenor of the note is not categorically negative and that it “leaves the
                    way open” for further consideration.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai and Peiping. Shanghai repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
